<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-034-191 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 457 397</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 14 1991 v25 n41 p39(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Windows tool vendors get back to basics. (applications programmersoffer simplified Microsoft Corp. Windows graphical user interfaceapplications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Daly, James.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many software companies announce they are offering less expensive,basic versions of popular Microsoft Windows graphical userinterface software packages to meet the needs of users who do notrequire complicated features.andP;  The companies hope thestripped-down versions will prompt customers to purchaseadditional office and home copies of software.andP;  Firms offeringpared-down applications include Asymetrix Corp, which is marketinglow-end database, presentation graphics and personal planningapplications, Borland International Inc and PowerUp Software Corp.andO;Firms hope to increase short-term revenues with the entry-levelpackages, but they also hope to gain customers who may eventuallyneed more complicated applications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Products)Borland International Inc. (Product development)Asymetrix Corp. (Product development).andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows (Graphical user interface) (Computer programs).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentMarketing StrategyUser NeedsPriceSoftware packagesGraphical user interface.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>